title: Grateful Dead Live at Capitol Theatre on 1977-04-27
description:
Set 1

The Promised Land
Mississippi Half-Step Uptown Toodeloo
Looks Like Rain
Sugaree
El Paso
Row Jimmy
New Minglewood Blues
Loser
The Music Never Stopped

Set 2

Estimated Prophet
Scarlet Begonias ->
Fire On The Mountain ->
Good Lovin'
Ramble On Rose
Samson And Delilah

Encore
Johnny B. Goode

reviews.review_text: Long Jams The long jams were very typical during the midddle '70's.  Great era to have gone thru!  Man I like many sure do miss the Dead.  Furthur isn't even close.......Phil Lesh and Friends almost got it...Garcia later.

Ditto Amen Deadheadable. I agree, can't get into the Further thing.  Phil had right idea, rotate two guitarists with a solid rhythm section and away we go...I always thought Phil should have been orchestrating the Grateful Dead setlists. Ratdog was good too, but The Other Ones, The Dead, Further, just won't be the same.  Back to this show, one of my all time favs, something about Jer's tone (being there may have helped) the band was on and the show is a masterpiece.  Almost has that Englishtown sound indoors, sort of.  Enjoy and Peace everyone

Great show Wish I could download this one.

Oh, and Furthur rocks.  You guys have your heads up your asses.  Probably Giants fans.
never Furthur than '81 I always liked this second set here. Nice early S>F, Good Lovin' is excellent and a killer Dew.

Pass on this one, head to May The sound is very good here, no problems with that.

The early part of 77 was uneven; they were still breaking in a lot of new songs.  In my opinion, Seventy-Seven (wish I had italics for that) didn't start until May.  That's when they started delivering consistently strong shows, with 5/8 being the best of the year and standing up with the best shows of all time.

I can't believe how many reviewers are praising this show up and down.  My advice to them is, listen to some more 77!  Really, someone called this Scarlet>Fire, a proto version at best, the best (s)he'd ever heard!  This show does have a nice 1/2-Step and Sugaree, a strong early Estimated (not sure how I feel about Keith's keyboard weirdness) and an outstanding Music (though I prefer the 80's versions when they took the little interlude in triplet rhythm in B and stretched it into a significant jam in its own right; a good example of that would be Hershey 6-27-85, though the best ever TMNS to my ears is 3-5-81).

About the Dew - it's a great version, and clearly shows that they were working on that double-time stomp that would culminate in the greatest-ever version of 5/8.  But it suffers from a lack of flow in the 2nd set.  It's like, song, song, song, song, Terrapin, Dew.  Whereas 5/8 is a mega jam that naturally, almost inevitably flows into and sets you up for the incredible Dew that follows as a logical progression that just FEELS right.  

Four stars mostly on the strength of the Dew.  Otherwise, this show is way below average for 77.

Love the 2nd Set Though I too am a huge fan of May '77 (Palladium on May 1 was the first of many a Dead show for me), I cannot ignore the depth of the boys performance in the 2nd set of this show. And though there are those who wouldcaution against this choice, the scarlet>fire combo is one of my favorites ever. I know every lick, every note as if I wrote it myself. We may bicker amongst ourselves with show vs show in a given year or even year vs. year in a given decade but really, who doesn't love the 70s as a whole. All the way through the decade I have favorites dating back to that Chateau d'Herouville gig in Herouville,  France on 6-21-71 where the original 5 played their asses off on the lawn behind the chateau. So many roads, so many favorites!

May 8 Grateful Phishmon, I'll see your May '77 and raise you Winterland: March 18-20, 1977.  That set the standard for the rest of the years.  :)

As far as 4/27 goes - this was one of my first tapes when I got back to college in the fall of '77.  I loved the punch and flow of the Scarlet > Fire > Good Lovin', dug Keith's space-synth riffs on Estimated, and had my mind blown by that titanic Terrapin > Dew.  If 3/18/77 (my first show) got me on the bus, my tape of 4/27/77 helped seal the deal.
- I don't know. The second set is pretty rad; I'm just not sure it's among the greats.

Hey grateful phishmon Don't be such a douche. We know how good May '77 is. NO this show is not as good as Cornell. YES it is worth listening to. I don't always need to hear a mind blowing May 77 show. Lots of those I heavily digested many years ago and it's great to hear '77 Dead that I'm not intimately familiar with.
